=== July 1891: Appointment and Salaries Ordinance ===
After the [[Promulgation of the Meiji Constitution]] on February 11, 1889, the December 24, 1889 [[Cabinet Ordinance]] (Imperial Ordinance No. 135) stipulated that appointments and dismissals of Chokunin and local government heads required Cabinet approval<ref>「内閣官制ヲ定ム」JACAR（アジア歴史資料センター）Ref.A15111667400、公文類聚・第十三編・明治二十二年・第二巻（国立公文書館）</ref>.

Subsequently, on July 24, 1891, the [[Appointment and Salaries Ordinance]] (Imperial Ordinance No. 82) abolished the earlier Kōtōkan Ranks and Salaries Ordinance. It retained the distinction between Chokunin and Sōnin-kan, but abolished official Ranks<ref name="July 1891 Appointment Ordinance">{{Wikiref|JACAR-A15112241100|JACAR：A15112241100}}</ref>.

=== November 1891: Classification Table ===
On November 14, 1891, the [[High-Ranking Civil and Military Officials Classification Table]] (Imperial Ordinance No. 215) established a 10-Rank system. Chokunin occupied the first to third Ranks, while Sōnin-kan occupied the fourth to tenth Ranks<ref>「御署名原本・明治二十四年・勅令第二百十五号・文武高等官官職等級表」JACAR（アジア歴史資料センター）Ref.A03020114700</ref>.

=== November 1892: Restoration of Rank and Salary System ===
In November 1892, the [[Rank and Salary Ordinance]] (Imperial Ordinance No. 96) reinstated the Rank system, replacing the 1891 ordinances<ref>{{Wikiref|JACAR-A15112439800|JACAR：A15112439800}}</ref>.

=== April 1946: Abolition of Kōtōkan ===
Under the [[Allied Occupation of Japan]], the Kōtōkan system was abolished on April 1, 1946, with the [[Officials Appointment and Classification Ordinance]] (Imperial Ordinance No. 190). Kōtōkan Ranks were reclassified into first and second-grade officials<ref name="Abolition of Kōtōkan 1946"/>.

== Officials under the Meiji Constitution ==
[[File:Kanri01.png|thumb|300px|Kōtōkan included parenthetical officials: Chokunin, Sōnin-kan, and Hannin-kan.]]
Under the [[Meiji Constitution]], national employees were classified as [[Kōtōkan]], [[Hannin-kan]], and others (employees, contractors, etc.), with distinct legal protections and privileges.

Kōtōkan were divided into [[civil service|civil]] and [[military Ranks]].

=== Chokunin ===
{{Main|Chokunin}}
'''Chokunin''' was the highest Kōtōkan Rank, appointed directly by the [[Emperor of Japan]].

=== Sōnin-kan ===
{{Main|Sōnin-kan}}
'''Sōnin-kan''' comprised Ranks three to nine, appointed by the Emperor based on recommendations by the Prime Minister or relevant ministers<ref name="March 1886 Kōtōkan Ordinance"/>.

=== Hannin-kan ===
{{Main|Hannin-kan}}
'''Hannin-kan''' was the Rank below Kōtōkan.

